<h2><B>Downloading the source code and the libraries</B></h2>

<p>If you want to program the chat tool, or if you want to use an experimental setup that relies on the Stanford Parser, Part of Speech Tagger, or Wordnet you will have to download all the sourcecode and libraries. The chat tool is stored in a repository
 on sourceforge.net. To download and install it, do the following:</p>


<ol>
          <li><p>Ensure you have <A HREF = "http://netbeans.org">netbeans</A> installed (version 7.0 or higher). Note, this isn't strictly necessary, you can of course use your own IDE, such as Eclipse. Or, if you want, you can also run the program from the command-line. However, it is easiest to run it from netbeans: when loaded from netbeans there is no need to play around with linking libraries and directory paths etc. The chat tool program should run "out of the box".</P></li>

          <li><p>Ensure you have the latest version of java installed. Installing netbeans should also install the correct version of java</P></li>

          <li><P>Ensure you have an SVN client, such as <A HREF = "http://tortoisesvn.net/">TortoiseSVN (on windows machines)</A>. If you have Mac OSX, follow <A HREF="http://blog.grapii.com/2012/08/svn-missing-in-mac-os-x-10-8-mountain-lion/"> these</A> instructions.</P></li>


          <li><P>Download the full source code of the project by doing an SVN checkout from the repository which is located at: <B>https://svn.code.sf.net/p/dietsourcecode/code/ </B>  On a linux machine you would type something like the following at the command prompt:</P>
              <B><P><code><FONT SIZE="4">svn co https://svn.code.sf.net/p/dietsourcecode/code/</FONT></code></B></P>
              (You might be prompted to install certificates - see this <A HREF = "https://sourceforge.net/p/forge/documentation/svn/">documentation.</A>)
              </li>
          <li>Follow the instructions in the user manual on how to use the chat tool to program and run experiments</li>

</ol>


